description: This table lists the tensor representations used for key variables in evolutionary multi-objective optimization (EMO) algorithms.  It shows how various aspects of the algorithms, such as population size, number of objectives, and problem dimensions, are represented using tensors, which are multi-dimensional arrays. These tensors are used in the proposed tensorization methodology for accelerating EMO algorithms on GPUs.

description: This table provides a detailed overview of the nine multiobjective robot control problems included in the MoRobtrol benchmark test suite. For each problem, it specifies the architecture of the multilayer perceptron (MLP) used for the control policy (MLP architecture), the number of parameters in the MLP (d), which represents the dimensionality of the problem, the number of objectives (m), and a concise description of the objectives (fv, fc, etc.).  The objectives represent various performance criteria of robot control tasks like forward reward, control cost, and energy consumption, allowing for the comprehensive evaluation of multiobjective optimization algorithms in realistic and challenging scenarios.

description: This table presents a statistical comparison of the performance of non-tensorized and tensorized versions of three Evolutionary Multi-Objective Optimization (EMO) algorithms (NSGA-III, MOEA/D, and HypE) across nine large-scale multiobjective optimization problem (LSMOP) instances (LSMOP1-LSMOP9).  For each algorithm and problem, the table shows the mean and standard deviation of the Inverted Generational Distance (IGD) metric, which measures the convergence and diversity of the obtained Pareto front, and the runtime in seconds.  The best results (lowest IGD and shortest runtime) for each problem are highlighted in bold, demonstrating the performance improvements achieved through tensorization.  All experiments were conducted using an RTX 4090 GPU.

caption: TABLE S.IV: The Reference Points of 9 MoRobtrol Problems for HV Calculation
description: This table lists the reference points used for hypervolume (HV) calculation in the nine multiobjective robot control problems of the MoRobtrol benchmark.  The reference point for each problem is a vector that defines the upper bound for the hypervolume calculation.  The HV calculation measures the volume of the objective space dominated by the obtained solutions and bounded by these reference points.  Different problems have different numbers of objectives and therefore different dimensional reference points.
